Start immediately:

Build a "proof of work" repo — one GitHub repo called something like learning-log. Every time you read or study anything, push one markdown file. Even 3 bullet points. The commit history becomes your artifact.
Never start a book without a question — before opening it, write one thing you want to be able to do or explain after. That becomes your float to watch.
Replace "finish chapter" with "find the answer" — read until your question gets answered, then stop. Close the book. Let the next question form naturally.


Build over the next few weeks:

Borrow the GitHub issues trick — open a GitHub Issue (even on a dummy repo) for each thing you're learning. Close it when you've applied the thing once. Closing issues feels exactly like shipping code.
Set a 2-hour obsession window, not a daily habit — instead of "20 mins every day," try "when I feel the pull, I go deep for 2 hours, no guilt if I skip tomorrow." Match your natural rhythm.
Make something embarrassingly small, publicly — tweet, post, or message one person what you learned this week. External witness = soft deadline.


The one meta-habit underneath all of these:
Whenever you set a new goal, ask yourself: "What's the float? How will I know within 30 minutes if I'm making progress?" If you can't answer that, redesign the goal before you start — not after you've already lost motivation.
